Document: what_are_godot_classes
Path: godot/tutorials/best_practices/what_are_godot_classes.rst
Summary: Explains how scripts and scenes in Godot can be thought of as classes and their role in applying object-oriented principles.

Applying object-oriented principles in Godot
The engine offers two main ways to create reusable objects: scripts and scenes. Neither of these technically define classes under the hood. Still, many best practices using Godot involve applying object-oriented programming principles to the scripts and scenes that compose your game. That is why it's useful to understand how we can think of them as classes. This guide briefly explains how scripts and scenes work in the engine's core to help you understand how they work under the hood.
---CHUNK---
Document: What Are Godot Classes  
Path: godot/tutorials/best_practices/what_are_godot_classes.rst  
Summary: Explains how Godot scripts extend built-in classes and interact with the ClassDB system.  

The engine provides built-in classes like Node. You can extend those to create derived types using a script. These scripts are not technically classes but resources that instruct the engine to perform initializations on built-in classes. Godot's internal classes use methods to register data with the ClassDB, a runtime database storing information about classes. ClassDB contains records for:  
- Properties.  
- Methods.  
- Constants.  
- Signals.  

When accessing a property or calling a method, objects check ClassDB records and base type records to determine if the operation is supported. Attaching a Script to an object extends the methods, properties, and signals available through ClassDB. Key Rule: Scripts without the "extends" keyword implicitly inherit from RefCounted, allowing instantiation from code but preventing attachment to Node.
---CHUNK---
Document: What Are Godot Classes  
Path: godot/tutorials/best_practices/what_are_godot_classes.rst  
Summary: Explains how scenes function similarly to classes in Godot, covering their structure, organization, and application of object-oriented principles.  

Scenes have many similarities to classes, making it reasonable to think of a scene as a class. Scenes are reusable, instantiable, and inheritable groups of nodes. Creating a scene is similar to having a script that creates nodes and adds them as children using `add_child()`.  

We often pair a scene with a scripted root node that utilizes the scene's nodes. This script extends the scene by adding behavior through imperative code. The content of a scene defines:  
- What nodes are available to the script.  
- How they are organized.  
- How they are initialized.  
- What signal connections they have with each other.  

Why is this important to scene organization? Because instances of scenes are objects. As a result, object-oriented principles like single responsibility and encapsulation apply to scenes. The scene is always an extension of the script attached to its root node, so it can be interpreted as part of a class. Most techniques in this best practices series build on this concept.